Pretty square with trees and flowers. It has relaxation areas and children's play areas. This garden pays tribute to the author, composer and performer, Francis Lemarque (1917-2002), singer of Paris populaire. It is divided into three spaces, each marked by different plant species which punctuate lights and colors according to the seasons.

On my other account I had reported a fountain vandalized for years, since then we have put it back into working order for some time but now it has been perhaps 3 months since the fountain has stopped working. The toilet caught fire about 2 months ago and it still hasn't been repaired (there was never any toilet paper). Shame. Today, December 25, so for perhaps 4 months, toilets are still under construction! View the photo. Today July 31, 2024 (7 months after my last notice) I report that the toilets have been repaired.
Small garden (opened in 2003) near rue de la Roquette. It offers a play area for children.

This square located at the corner of rue de la Roquette and Passage Charles Dallery is a very interesting place.  A chance to discover a book by Franz Olivier Giesbert entitled "The end of an era" which I really liked.  This book taught me that you should never let the pig and the fox form an alliance, otherwise they would end up eating the whole farm.  I highly recommend this book to anyone interested in farm stories.  More seriously, this place is perfect for children looking for sand and "kid's responsive" facilities and for parents wanting to take their young offspring out in search of a little greenery.

They removed the bushes... It's distressing. This square has changed a lot. Are they still the same owners? The experience boils down to sitting and admiring a large litter box in which animals are defecating. Disreputable
